06865nam a22007455i 9780773583825DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t20152015xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735838257 a10.1515/97807735838252doi  a(DE-B1597)657135  a(OCoLC)914189070  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aJL86.D42b.S838 2015 7aPOL0560002bisacsh04a363.34/622302aA Subtle Balance :bExpertise, Evidence, and Democracy in Public Policy and Governance, 1970-2010 /ced. by Edward A. Parson. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[2015] 4c©2015  a1 online resource :b2 tables, 4 figures  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tTables and Figures -- tAcknowledgments -- tA Subtle Balance: Editor’s Introduction -- tPublic Policy Analysis in Canada: A Forty-Year Overview -- tAffairs of the Smart: Will Researchers and Decision-Makers ȜHook Upȝ? -- tExpertise and Evidence in Public Policy: In Defence of (a Little) Technocracy -- tProgram Evaluation and Aboriginal Affairs: A History and a Thought Experiment -- tThe Canada Pension Plan and Policy Reform: Shifting Spaces for Democratic Deliberation -- tTales of Quantitative Analysis and Public Policy -- tEnvironmental Issues: Fifty Years of Change and Current Challenges -- tClimate Engineering: New Challenges for Scientific Assessment and Global Governance -- tSeeing Like a Sound? Resource Management and Property Rights in Clayoquot Sound -- tProfits v. Purpose: Hybrid Companies and the Charitable Dollar -- tThe Future of Computer-Supported Policy Analysis: Collaboration, Openness, Collective Intelligence, and Competition -- tIt’s Not My Problem: Personal Moral Responsibility for Policy Advice -- tWhat is an Honest Policy Analyst to Do? -- tSpeaking Elusive Truth to Shifting Power: Reflections on Evolving Styles, Changing Views, and New Problems -- tA Subtle Balance: Reflection and Synthesis -- tReferences -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aA Subtle Balance critically reflects on major trends and enduring challenges over the last four decades of public policy and governance. During this time, a tension has existed between two aims for public decisions: that they be based on the best available evidence and analysis, and that they be fully democratic. This period has seen a continuing drive for more direct citizen engagement in decision-making and governments trying to address major policy issues through novel consultative and collaborative processes. In essays that offer detailed and novel insights into the recent history of specific issues in social policy, environmental policy, and processes of policy advice and decision-making, contributors elaborate on how these trends have played out in diverse areas of practice, what their consequences have been, and how specific institutional reforms could reset the requisite balance between expertise, evidence, and democracy in Canadian public policy. Inspired by the wide-ranging contributions to scholarship and practice of A.R. (Rod) Dobell, A Subtle Balance draws on the influences of distinguished scholars and sophisticated practitioners of public policy to assess recent changes in governance. Contributors include Martin Bunton, Barry Carin, Ian Clark, Rachel Culley, Rod Dobell, Lia Ernst, Jill Horwitz, John Langford, Justin Longo, Michael Prince, Harry Swain, Charles Ungerleider, Josee van Eijndhoven, Michael Wolfson, and David Zussman.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aPublic administration -- Canada -- Decision making -- History -- 20th century. 0aPublic administration -- Canada -- Decision making -- History -- 21st century. 0aPublic administ